{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c75591f1-2c51-4008-bde2-e3f088ebcfb2","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\nKey differences: xUnit embeds the skip reason in the test attribute itself (`Fact`/`Theory`), while the others use a separate attribute.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e336cc2e-a9c6-4151-b6e9-2be1ae154866","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":310,"requestId":"083B:204131:86DE8CD:9535F9B:69EAC2E0"},"id":"510ba157-9b21-4c42-b023-d53196c79795","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:10:06.209Z","parentId":"8fa967cf-e906-477b-89df-c856e610a419"}
